    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.23.7"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Neihardt Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">7</fw>
                
                <figure/>
                5302 Stephen Lochner
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Dec. 4, 1950</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Friends&#8212;</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>So sorry I missed you in Chicago&#8212; but hope our paths cross again one day. I was thankful that I saw Black Elk. His condition was pitiful, + I stayed only 5 or 10 min. on each little visit. Sometimes he said <unclear reason="illegible">wise</unclear> + friendly things. Henry told me that the old man told him he would know the night of his death (if Henry was away) by watching the sky bec. the stars would dance. Exactly 3 w'ks after
                
                    <note><hi rend="caps">PRINTED IN SWITZERLAND</hi></note>
                
                    I left Pine Ridge Black Elk died. The school teacher, Mrs. Jacques, at Manderon wrote me that there was the most glorious display of the Aurora Borealis the night after Black Elk died- Possibly Henry misunderstood. I think the old man must have seen a vision of his death + probably said there would be "dancing lights" in the sky, + Henry thought he meant stars.</p>
                
                <p>All best wishes for Christmas + the New Year + the state of the world!</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Cordially yours</salute>
                    <signed>Carol Baumann</signed>         
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
